<!-- 5. PAGE TITLE --> <td colspan="3" id="content">
            <h2><font style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(0, 102, 0);"
 size="+1"><big><span style="color: rgb(0, 51, 51);">HOME</span><br>
            </big></font></h2>

            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="content-sub"><big
 style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Bundle-Exchange-Compute (BEC) is a parallel
programming model developed at Sandia National Labs, in collaboration with Syracuse University.</span></big><br
 style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;">
            <ul style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;">
              <li><font size="-1"> BEC supports virtual shared memory
programming. </font></li>
              <li><font size="-1"> BEC includes <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">an extension to C for shared variables</span>,
and a portable runtime library <span style="font-weight: bold;">(BEC
Lib)</span>.</font></li>

              <li><font size="-1"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Compatible
with MPI</span>: BEC code and MPI code can intermix.<br>
                </font></li>
              <li><font size="-1"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Good
application performance</span> (compatible with MPI) </font></li>
              <li><font size="-1"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Easy
to use</span> (much easier than MPI): BEC programmers are free from
explicit management of data distribution and locality, communication,
and synchronization. BEC makes programming of complex unstructured
communication patterns very easy. </font></li>
            </ul>

            <div
 style="text-align: left; font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"><big><small
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(0, 102, 0);" size="+1"><small><br>
            <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Programming in BEC</span></small></font></small></small></small><br>
            </big></div>
            <font style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"
 size="+1"><big> <small><small><font size="-1">A BEC program has
shared
variables
and code sections that typically repeat the Bundle-Exchange-Compute
phases. For example,</font><br>
            </small></small></big></font>
            <div
 style="margin-left: 40px; font-family: times new roman,times,serif; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 204);"><small
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font size="+1"><small><small>shared
int
A[10000], B[10000], C[10000];&nbsp;&nbsp; /* globally shared data
structures */</small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">

            <small style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 size="+1"><small><small>&#8230;</small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
            <small style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 size="+1"><small><small>BEC_request(A[3]);&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
/* Shared
data needs to be requested before
use&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; */ </small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
            <small style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 size="+1"><small><small>BEC_request(B[8]);&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
/* Such
requests will be <span style="font-weight: bold;">Bundle</span>d by
the runtime library&nbsp; */</small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">

            <small style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 size="+1"><small><small>BEC_exchange();&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
/* <span style="font-weight: bold;">Exchange</span> bundled requests
globally&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
*/ </small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
            <small style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 size="+1"><small><small>C[10] =
A[3]+B[8];&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; /*
After exchange, <span style="font-weight: bold;">compute</span> C[10]
using A[3] and B[8] as if
they were local. </small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">

            <small style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><small><small><font
 size="+1"><small><small>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Shared
location C[10] will be updated </small></small></font><font size="+1"><small><small>in
the
next round of global exchange */ </small></small></font></small></small></small><br
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
            <small style="color: rgb(51, 204, 0);"><font size="+1"><small><span
 style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">&#8230;</span><br style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">
            <br>
            </small></font></small></div>

            <div
 style="text-align: left; font-family: times new roman,times,serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><font
 style="font-weight: bold; font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"
 size="3">Using BEC<br>
            </font>
            <ul style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;">
              <li style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"><font
 size="-1"><font color="#000000">BEC
= (C language extension for shared variables) + (BEC Lib)</font></font></li>
              <li style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"><font
 size="-1">BEC Lib can be used with or without
the language
extension.&nbsp;</font></li>
              <li style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;"><font
 size="-1">BEC can be used alone, or as
enhancements to MPI and other programming languages/models.&nbsp;</font></li>
              <li><small><font
 style="font-family: times new roman,times,serif;" size="-1"><font
 color="#000000">BEC
is readily portable to
any machine (including PC) with a C/C++ compiler, Unix/Linux, and a
message-passing library such as MPI.</font></font><br>

                </small></li>
            </ul>
            <br>
            </div>
<!-- end content area --><!-- "Top of page" anchor may be removed if not needed -->
